 On Jan 22, Matthew Flatt wrote:
 > The launcher isn't a MrEd launcher any more, so using the form GUI
 > is a problem, right?
 
 (It probably wouldn't be too difficult to refactor things up so the
 mzscheme version does some limited textual form.  But the web page is
 definitely a better solution, I think.)
 
 
 > How much do we rely on information gathered from the user's computer
 > (by the current "send a bug report" form)? I'm sometimes grateful to
 > be certain that I know which platform is involved, but mostly the
 > web form seems to work ok.
 
 FWIW, besides the platform (as below) and the version (embeded in the
 URL somehow), there is the set of collections and the language level
 that are sometimes useful.
 
 
 On Jan 22, Robby Findler wrote:
 > On Jan 22, 2008 10:54 AM, Matthew Flatt <mflatt@cs.utah.edu> wrote:
 > >
 > > Via Javascript, or something like that?
 > 
 > Not javascript. The browser sends an identifying string already when
 > submitting a form.
 
 I think that browsers mostly send the agent version line, and I think
 that Apache's CGI interface puts that in an environment variable.  It
 should be an editable field though, since some people use a different
 system to browse.  (Like me, who usually work on linux through VNC,
 but I browse with my local (Windows) browser.)
 
 
 > > Sounds like a good idea; can we make that improvement immediately?
 > 
 > Someone could, I guess.
 
 I'll look into this now.
 
 
 On Jan 22, Matthew Flatt wrote:
 > At Tue, 22 Jan 2008 10:55:33 -0600, "Robby Findler" wrote:
 > > 
 > > Not javascript. The browser sends an identifying string already
 > > when submitting a form.
 > 
 > That seems to late. Don't we want to initialize the field, but let
 > someone change it in case they're submitting a bug report about a
 > different platform?
 
 (I should have read through...)  I think that putting it in an
 editable field will work fine.  In other words, the interaction goes
 like this:
 
 * Browser on the start page, click on the bug link which has the
   version in some way like:
     http://bugs.plt-scheme.org/?v=3.99.0.9
 
 * The cgi script gets the URL and the AGENT info and composes the HTML
   that makes up the form with the string in it -- but in an editable
   field.  That should apply for the version too.
 
 * The user verifies/edits the fields and submits
 
 * At this point the cgi script is just passing the values on, no
   further editing.
 
 
 On Jan 22, Robby Findler wrote:
 > 
 > That would be better, yes.
 > 
 > We could also use that javascript (assumign someone implements and
 > maintains it) to select the right download automatically.
 
 You mean for the download page?  That's less useful, I think, since
 it's more common to download on one platform and install on another.
 
 
 > I believe this is painful and, of course, a moving target. But perhaps
 > there are javascript frameworks out there that we can use?
 
 Probably, if you really want that.
 
