Subject: Re: [plt-bug] all/9124: No "submit bug report" in plt-help
Date: Tue, 22 Jan 2008 14:46:47 -0500

 On Jan 22, Robby Findler wrote:
 > CGI seems way better, esp. since this one can be a very simple
 > script, presumably requiring very little work on the server side.
 > 
 > I think that the Javascript is going to be much harder to maintain.
 
 Actually, both of these are wrong...
 
 The reason that it's not simple is that the CGI script needs to spit
 out the usual code (eg, the title bar with the logo, the search box,
 the google widget that collects statistics).  This would be simple
 only with some magical "reflect" form that produces Scheme code that
 will reliable produce the same static HTML with some values spliced
 in.  (Easiest would be with some file that will be copied, but that
 needs to work on v3xx and v4 since the machine still has v3.)
 
 The Javascript is not really that hard -- all it needs to do is to use
 something like `navigator.platform' which (AFAICT from googling
 around) is supported by all browsers.
 
